The WASP-163 Exoplanetary System


Overview

WASP-163 is a star with 0.97 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.01 times its radius. It is located 858.74 light years away from the solar system.

WASP-163 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the WASP-163 system


WASP-163 b

WASP-163 b was discovered by the SuperWASP-South observatory using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.03 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of WASP-163 b is 594.6600000000001 times the mass of Earth. The radius of WASP-163 b is 13.473 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, WASP-163 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
